al to modern life as power and water, a way to teach critical judgment and inspire national pride. It helped people to forget the past, voice conflicting aspirations, and imagine a shared future. Based on a dazzling survey of archival material, Pasler's rich interdisciplinary work looks beyond elites and the histories their agendas have dominated to open new windows onto the musical tastes and practices of amateurs as well as professionals. A fascinating history of the period emerges, one rooted in political realities and the productive tensions between the political and the aesthetic. Highly evocative and deeply humanistic, Composing the Citizen ignites broad debates about music's role in democracy and its meaning in our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusicxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  a1871.  aaesthetics.  aartists.  ademocracy.  adiscussion books.  aeffect of music.  aengaging.  afrance.  afrench people.  afrench society.  aglobal politics.  amodern history.  amodern life.  amodern music.  amusic history.  amusic.  amusicians.  anational identity.  anational pride.  anonfiction.  aperforming arts.  apolitical.  apublic policy.  apublic utility.  arole of music.  atheoretical.  athird republic france.  athought provoking.  avalue of music.  awestern music.  awestern society.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025740540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094387240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943872423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943872/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University 